summary: I am a professional musician as the drummer for Cheshire Grin, Dmanzland, Omega Train, and Strumberry Pie. I am also a licensed social worker in the state of New Jersey with an MSW from Rutgers, the State University of New Jersey, a BA in psychology from Monmouth University, and an AA in music from Brookdale Community College. My background in music, academia, research, and the working world has allowed me to exercise a diverse range of skills, such as creative thinking, a connection-driven approach to working with people, an orientation towards individual and group/team goals, a leadership style that accounts for all voices, and a wide array of skills in research, including literature review, design, analysis, and writing. These skills come from a diverse history of experiences, including being an active musician for 14 years, coaching drums for students of all ages, involving myself in research during my undergraduate years (including conducting my own study and leading a team of research assistants in data collection), and interning and working in the world of therapy.

currentPositions.description: I provide individual therapy sessions at the outpatient level for adult clients from an eclectic approach heavily informed by cognitive-behavioral and mindfulness orientations.

projects.description:
My friend Cassie Passantino was a film major at Hofstra University and reached out to me to create the musical score for her senior thesis film, The Act. The film is about a musical, so before shooting could begin we had to create the musical, presented as a mini progressive rock opera. I wrote the music and lyrics, recorded the drum tracks, and programmed and recorded MIDI keyboards and pads. My friend and then-bandmate Ross Owen recorded guitars and bass and engineered the sound. Once the instrumentals were completed, lead vocals were recorded by three of the film's actresses and backup vocals were recorded by a children's choir of intermediate school students. I engineered the vocal sessions.

Due to the COVID-19 outbreak, further production was postponed. A virtual version of the film was presented to Hofstra University film professors and senior-level students via Zoom.
projects.title: The Act (Music from the Short Film)

projects.description:
This study was based on my senior thesis.

Abstract: The ability to recognize emotion in speech is a critical skill for social communication. Motivated by previous work that has shown that vocal emotion recognition accuracy varies by musical ability, the current study addressed this relationship using a behavioral measure of musical ability (i.e., singing) that relies on the same effector system used for vocal prosody production. In the current study, participants completed a musical production task that involved singing four-note novel melodies. To measure pitch perception, we used a simple pitch discrimination task in which participants indicated whether a target pitch was higher or lower than a comparison pitch. We also used self-report measures to address language and musical background. We report that singing ability, but not self-reported musical experience nor pitch discrimination ability, was a unique predictor of vocal emotion recognition accuracy. These results support a relationship between processes involved in vocal production and vocal perception, and suggest that sensorimotor processing of the vocal system is recruited for processing vocal prosody.
projects.title: Singing Ability is Related to Emotion Recognition: Evidence for Shared Sensorimotor Processing Across Speech and Music

message.text: Instagram / TikTok info compilations can be interesting thought generators. They are not, however, the end of the mental health conversation.

I fear for the people who get their mental health advice from TikTok and Instagram.

Lots of overconfident ‘experts’.

Too much unearned certainty.

Not enough nuance. 

The longer I’ve been in mental health professionally (going on 15 years now), the more I answer “it depends.”

Is that person you’re dating avoidant, or just not into you? I don’t know. Depends.

Are you the way you are because of how your parents treated you? Dunno. Maybe. Maybe it’s genetics. Can’t be sure.

I’d make a really bad TikTok ✨trauma coach✨

But LinkedIn is different. The posts can be long enough for nuance and complexity.

The human condition is complex. Mental health discussion should be too.
This is so important, especially for musicians who have interests outside of pleasing the general audience.
Do things for your own satisfaction. Consider praise from others to be a bonus. If you don't work for their validation in the first place, you won't need it to feel satisfied once it's done.
🎶 And musicians and artists, because we need time to create to fulfill our true purpose

Not everyone thrives in the office 9-5

Flexible working is for 👇

🩸 People with periods, because menstruation sucks

👩‍⚕️ People with caring responsibilities, because life is hard to manage

🦉 Night owls, because some people do their best work at odd hours

😷 Individuals with chronic conditions, as our bodies can be unpredictable

🛩 People who have emigrated, because they still want to see their families

🫱🏻‍🫲🏾 People of colour, because racism and microaggressions in offices are real

👶 Working mothers, of course, as women still do the majority of the childcare

♿️ People with disabilities, because the traditional in-office 9-5 can be unworkable

🧠 Neurodivergent individuals, because sometimes the brain does not brain when and where you want it to

🧔🏽 Working fathers, because men want to be there for their children too, despite what society might encourage

🏳️‍🌈 LGBTQIA+ individuals, because not everyone is out at work, and discrimination is definitely still a thing

What examples have I missed? Tell me in the comments 👇

Companies embracing flexible working are creating a more inclusive and equitable world of work.

Without flexible working, there are tens of millions of people who could not work a full-time role, or would be miserable doing so (I was one ☝️)

Kudos to those companies on Flexa who are embracing flexibility and creating more inclusive hiring processes ✌️

#FlexibleWorking #RemoteWorking #DiversityAndInclusion
